i### Passion and Curiosity	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iOne might wonder why people continue to invent new esoteric	/	tilde.team	70
ilanguages, since there is no financial gain to be had. I	/	tilde.team	70
ithink the main reasons are passion and curiosity. A passion	/	tilde.team	70
ifor computer science and programming, and the curiosity to	/	tilde.team	70
iseek out alternative things on the Internet.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Humans Only	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iDespite all the hype surrounding generative AI, I get the	/	tilde.team	70
iimpression that esoteric languages remain a field studied	/	tilde.team	70
ilargely by human minds alone. This can be explained by the	/	tilde.team	70
ilack of commercial objectives; after all, the authors and	/	tilde.team	70
idevelopers of these languages aren’t getting paid.	/	tilde.team	70
iFurthermore, it’s a subject that doesn’t interest companies	/	tilde.team	70
ibecause they can’t make a profit from it, and it’s not a	/	tilde.team	70
itopic that comes up in business settings either. It’s not a	/	tilde.team	70
imainstream computer science subject, and demand is very low.	/	tilde.team	70
iIn the end, only enthusiasts and the curious remain—those	/	tilde.team	70
iwho simply want to have fun.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iAn esoteric programming language that isn’t a product of the	/	tilde.team	70
ihuman mind loses all its charm and appeal. These languages	/	tilde.team	70
iare complex for the human brain, but much less so for an	/	tilde.team	70
iartificial brain, such as an LLM.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
